docs.abstract: USAReally might look like any other fledgling news organization. But some cybersecurity experts believe it may be part of a retooled Russian propaganda operation.
docs.snippet: USAReally might look like any other fledgling news organization. But some cybersecurity experts believe it may be part of a retooled Russian propaganda operation.
docs.lead_paragraph: To an untrained eye, USAReally might look like any other fledgling news organization vying for attention in a crowded media landscape. Its website publishes a steady stream of stories on hot-button political issues like race, immigration and income inequality. It has reader polls, a video section and a daily podcast.

headline.main: Is a New Russian Meddling Tactic Hiding in Plain Sight?
headline.print_headline: Russian Website, in Plain View, Stokes the Fire of U.S. Politics

docs.snippet: The unsigned decisions, without noted dissents, indicated that the court continued to support the widely criticized doctrine of qualified immunity.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In two unsigned decisions without noted dissents, the Supreme Court on Monday ruled in favor of police officers accused of using excessive force. The rulings were a signal that the court continues to support the doctrine of qualified immunity, which can shield police misconduct from lawsuits seeking damages.

headline.main: In Two Rulings, Supreme Court Bolsters Legal Shield for Police
headline.print_headline: Legal Shield For Officers Is Bolstered In 2 Decisions
